WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.240
My goal at the end of this talk is you walk away learning something, whether it's just

00:00:09.240 --> 00:00:15.440
about an R package or you have some new strategies in terms of approaching some of your more

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:22.600
technical solutions with end users or clients or what have you.

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:23.879
So quick introduction.

00:00:23.879 --> 00:00:25.240
My name is Tanya Cashorali.

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:31.559
I got my first start with R in 2005.

00:00:31.559 --> 00:00:38.320
I was working at Children's Hospital Informatics Program analyzing genetic data, and I've been

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:39.439
using it ever since.

00:00:39.439 --> 00:00:46.119
I love R. I started my own company based out of Boston called TCB Analytics in 2015, and

00:00:46.119 --> 00:00:47.400
I always have to include Porkchop.

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:48.880
He's my assistant.

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:53.279
You may see him come in here at some point, but you feel free to contact me through any

00:00:53.279 --> 00:00:54.279
of these avenues.

00:00:54.279 --> 00:01:01.080
I'm more than happy to answer questions if we don't have enough time either.

00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:03.880
So what is anomaly detection?

00:01:03.880 --> 00:01:05.760
This is just the Wikipedia definition.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:09.760
It's sometimes referred to as outlier detection, but I like to say it gets a little fancier

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:14.320
than just detecting standard deviations above or below a mean.

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:17.320
It's a way to identify rare items or events.

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:21.559
I typically use it for time series data.

00:01:21.559 --> 00:01:25.879
Twitter actually developed a package, which I'll get into, and they use it to look at

00:01:25.879 --> 00:01:27.440
tweets per second.

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:32.559
You can use it for CPU metrics and utilization, but I'll talk about two different industry

00:01:32.559 --> 00:01:40.199
cases in which we were able to use it and had a lot of success doing so.

00:01:40.199 --> 00:01:44.320
So the R package, like I said, was developed first at Twitter, and there's some really

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:46.160
good papers that I link at the end of this.

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:47.839
The slides are available.

00:01:47.839 --> 00:01:49.320
I definitely recommend it.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:50.320
There's some good reading in there.

00:01:50.559 --> 00:01:57.160
I won't have time to get into all the technical details, but I actually used a fork from HarborMaster,

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:04.279
and he made a few modifications to the package, one of which is it returns tidy data frames,

00:02:04.279 --> 00:02:09.800
tibbles, and he also made the function names a little easier, snake case aliases, so you

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:15.479
can see them, ADTS for time series and ADVEC for vector.

00:02:15.479 --> 00:02:17.360
So this is the package.

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:21.399
It's been phenomenal for us so far.

00:02:21.399 --> 00:02:27.880
Now just to talk about the implementation or the underlying algorithm, very briefly,

00:02:27.880 --> 00:02:33.360
it builds upon an extreme studentized deviant test, just a big word for saying it does some

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:39.360
time series decomposition and robust statistics, and the paper I mentioned actually benchmarks

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:46.039
these four approaches, quant linear, a seasonal decomposition with loss, and a quant spline.

00:02:46.039 --> 00:02:52.440
The one they said actually performed the best was piecewise median, so it looked like

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:57.639
stable metrics typically exhibited very little change in the median over two-week windows,

00:02:57.639 --> 00:03:01.800
so it defaults to breaking your data into two-week windows and calculating a moving

00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:02.800
median.

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:07.240
It also accounts for intraday and weekly seasonalities.

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:11.279
It was pretty much performing on par with these more expensive calculations.

00:03:12.039 --> 00:03:17.199
Four times faster than the other ones, so that's the red line you're seeing here.

00:03:17.199 --> 00:03:22.080
We've had no performance issues and have given it quite a bit of data, and we run everything

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:25.800
in real time.

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:31.160
So I love that this track is also called working with people, because it's the hardest thing

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:32.160
we do.

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:37.320
R and code and math is typically easy compared to working with people, and that's what we

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:39.800
do day to day.

00:03:39.839 --> 00:03:44.440
Typically, the problems when implementing complex technical solutions comes down to

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:45.639
communication breakdown.

00:03:45.639 --> 00:03:51.039
It always comes down to that, between developers and end-users typically.

00:03:51.039 --> 00:03:55.399
So oftentimes, we'll get a set of initial requirements, and when building data products,

00:03:55.399 --> 00:03:58.639
they almost always change or get thrown out the window.

00:03:58.639 --> 00:04:02.399
There's just so much that any end-user, I don't care how much you know the product or

00:04:02.399 --> 00:04:06.279
the data, there's so many things you'll never be able to predict, and that could happen

00:04:06.279 --> 00:04:08.679
as soon as you start building.

00:04:08.679 --> 00:04:12.199
Before an app gets into production, it just doesn't meet the end-user's expectations.

00:04:12.199 --> 00:04:16.000
They may have given you a mock-up or a wireframe, but there were a whole bunch of other edge

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.040
cases that they just didn't think of that they wanted to tackle, and we see that happen

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:22.519
a lot.

00:04:22.519 --> 00:04:26.679
And this happens because not all users have the technical understanding.

00:04:26.679 --> 00:04:31.440
Sometimes they have a limited understanding of the statistical processes and principles,

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:35.320
and then developers may just take those user requirements and run with them, and they disappear

00:04:35.320 --> 00:04:38.600
and come back with an end product.

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:44.000
Lastly, developers, they're not always including those users, so you don't want to disappear

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:49.760
and then just come back to the user with something that they may have not actually wanted.

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:54.640
So part of that art is figuring out exactly what the user does want compared to what they're

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:55.640
telling you.

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:58.519
And that's where Shiny comes into play.

00:04:58.519 --> 00:05:05.279
So we've had a lot of success just taking ideas, connecting to real data, and showing

00:05:05.279 --> 00:05:08.760
the user something tangible, something that they can interact with.

00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:14.799
And what we found is using Shiny as a collaboration aid, we see those requirements quickly change,

00:05:14.799 --> 00:05:18.880
we see the user get excited because they're now touching something real and working with

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:21.559
something real, and they feel more engaged.

00:05:21.559 --> 00:05:25.040
They feel a sense of ownership that typically they wouldn't have if you were just a developer

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:29.760
off doing your own thing, and disappearing for weeks or months, and then coming back

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:34.799
with something that they didn't necessarily feel like they were a part of.

00:05:34.799 --> 00:05:39.839
So this is what I like to call rapid prototyping, and it enables you to demonstrate value before

00:05:39.839 --> 00:05:42.799
doing this full-scale implementation, and it enables you to find all these different

00:05:42.799 --> 00:05:49.200
edge cases, and data scientists can focus on problem-solving instead of having to play

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:51.440
this back and forth of, well, what exactly do you want?

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:56.279
You can solve a problem quickly, come back, show the client something, and then keep iterating

00:05:56.279 --> 00:06:00.880
that way.

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:04.079
So to get into the examples, this first one I think is pretty cool.

00:06:04.079 --> 00:06:08.000
It's a hardware manufacturer in life sciences.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:13.320
They essentially build the rapid blood testing machines in hospitals.

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:18.160
So if you go to the hospital, hopefully not, when you're there and you get your blood taken,

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:22.839
this is the company creating the devices that give you those rapid results.

00:06:22.839 --> 00:06:27.600
They have sensors in them that relay quantitative metrics and help diagnose instrument failures,

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:33.920
but what this company was doing was deploying the hardware in the field and finding out

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:38.119
retroactively that there was a problem, so they would take the machine back and analyze

00:06:38.119 --> 00:06:41.359
all of the data coming off the machines.

00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:44.519
This seemed like a perfect opportunity to use anomaly detection.

00:06:44.519 --> 00:06:49.920
We wanted to identify those problems before they went out into the field.

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:52.720
So here's what the data and experimentation looks like.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:54.880
We have various metrics coming off these machines.

00:06:54.880 --> 00:07:01.119
There are things like protein levels and analytes, and they come off at different aggregations,

00:07:01.119 --> 00:07:05.200
24 hours, 12 hours, et cetera.

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:09.160
This anomaly detection function has a bunch of parameters, and we just played around with

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:13.679
some of them and iterated on things like, what percentage of the data should we capture

00:07:13.679 --> 00:07:15.559
anomalies for?

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:20.959
Should it be positive and negative direction, so above or below the expected threshold?

00:07:20.959 --> 00:07:23.799
The level of significance, maybe we really need to be stringent here.

00:07:23.799 --> 00:07:29.019
Maybe we can only go with 90% confidence versus 99%.

00:07:29.019 --> 00:07:32.220
And then that piecewise median period that I mentioned.

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:35.959
Another thing we realized was there are some outliers that are just insane, and anomaly

00:07:35.959 --> 00:07:41.440
detection would always pick up, and that's very indicative of a hardware failure, but

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:42.799
the client already knew about these.

00:07:42.920 --> 00:07:48.399
They said, well, we know that these are problematic, so we actually did some outlier removal and

00:07:48.399 --> 00:07:53.200
then ran the anomaly detection, and, of course, then there were no anomalies detected.

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:58.160
The input data very much makes a difference on your end results.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:02.880
So those are all parameters we wanted to play with, and we were literally manually analyzing

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:08.839
all of this, and it turns out putting it into a Shiny app and just allowing myself and the

00:08:08.839 --> 00:08:13.440
client to play with these different parameters, we quickly got feedback on, hey, this actually

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:15.359
looks like a good threshold to use.

00:08:15.359 --> 00:08:16.359
These are good parameters.

00:08:16.359 --> 00:08:19.160
Let's run with these.

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:23.559
From there, we thought, well, instead of this sort of top-down approach and exploring all

00:08:23.559 --> 00:08:27.079
the different options, let's alert the user on exactly where to go.

00:08:27.079 --> 00:08:32.400
So we took the high-significance anomalies, highlighted them, and allowed the user to

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:33.719
then click one.

00:08:33.719 --> 00:08:38.239
So I want to know more about this one, what's going on with potassium or calcium, and it

00:08:38.239 --> 00:08:42.039
would bring you right back to that screen, pre-populate all the parameters, again, just

00:08:42.039 --> 00:08:46.559
a nice little user experience thing, time saver, and they could dig into the details

00:08:46.559 --> 00:08:49.840
a little more.

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:51.559
The code was pretty straightforward.

00:08:51.559 --> 00:08:54.520
The input data looks just like you'd expect for a time series.

00:08:54.520 --> 00:08:57.820
There's a timestamp and a measure.

00:08:57.820 --> 00:09:01.159
We iterated over the different significance values.

00:09:01.159 --> 00:09:05.440
We also defaulted to using one year of data prior to the date range that the client is

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:06.440
actually interested in.

00:09:06.719 --> 00:09:12.919
So if I care about May of 2020, let's start with data from May 1st of 2019 to get some

00:09:12.919 --> 00:09:20.359
of that seasonality, and more data is better for this type of algorithm.

00:09:20.359 --> 00:09:24.479
But throughout the project, they then informed us, hey, we actually have these limits that

00:09:24.479 --> 00:09:25.479
we already know.

00:09:25.479 --> 00:09:28.520
It's like you could consider it a prior in Bayesian math.

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:34.039
And so upper limit, lower limit is something that they would say these are automatically

00:09:34.039 --> 00:09:35.039
bad.

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:39.679
This seems like it's guiding us a little more, and we could probably integrate this.

00:09:39.679 --> 00:09:44.599
First we started with a completely data-driven approach, agnostic from any business logic.

00:09:44.599 --> 00:09:47.760
But then we said, well, maybe we can incorporate these limits.

00:09:47.760 --> 00:09:52.559
And even giving them a simple tool like this to explore those different outliers was something

00:09:52.559 --> 00:09:59.479
that they didn't have, and they were really doing this all pretty manually and by hand.

00:09:59.479 --> 00:10:03.000
So then we combined those rules with the anomaly detection.

00:10:03.039 --> 00:10:04.960
This is over a course of a few months.

00:10:04.960 --> 00:10:05.960
We got better and better.

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:07.400
We were finding these parameters.

00:10:07.400 --> 00:10:11.960
So now the colors you see here, the green is just an anomaly that the algorithm found

00:10:11.960 --> 00:10:14.479
based on the parameters we already tweaked.

00:10:14.479 --> 00:10:19.239
The blue means it's approaching that threshold limit, and these lines, these vertical lines

00:10:19.239 --> 00:10:23.679
are those thresholds, which vary by analyte.

00:10:23.679 --> 00:10:25.599
And then the red is both.

00:10:25.599 --> 00:10:31.000
So we decided these are probably most important to look at because there's strong signal here.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.760
Not only are you approaching a limit, but the anomaly detection is saying this is trending

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:41.000
differently based on this piecewise median.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.359
The other thing we did was allow the user to specify how stringent they wanted this

00:10:45.359 --> 00:10:46.640
approaching limit to be.

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:49.599
So here you can see it's not that close to the line.

00:10:49.599 --> 00:10:51.799
We were able to define thresholds.

00:10:51.799 --> 00:10:56.440
Maybe they really wanted to get close, and the way we did that was based on quartiles.

00:10:56.440 --> 00:11:00.479
So the closer they were to the quartile of that range, the top quartile, that was more

00:11:00.479 --> 00:11:06.599
stringent and so on, and we let them kind of open up the lens, so to speak, to be looser

00:11:06.599 --> 00:11:09.039
or more stringent.

00:11:09.039 --> 00:11:11.400
This ended up being the best approach for the client.

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:17.440
Just not only was it the algorithm, but incorporating the business logic as well.

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:22.080
So I want to jump quickly into the next example so that we have time for questions.

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:26.400
The other example, and I should wrap up also that they're using this on a day-to-day basis.

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:27.760
It runs as a Shiny app.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:34.520
They're able to connect live to their database, and it's been used as a tool to basically

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:39.239
direct their investigation and identify these hardware failures before the machines get

00:11:39.239 --> 00:11:40.359
shipped out to the hospitals.

00:11:40.359 --> 00:11:46.280
So we think that's a really cool application, and it's R and Shiny.

00:11:46.280 --> 00:11:49.280
The price tag is pretty good.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:53.599
So real-world example, again, is another client that works in the sports and entertainment

00:11:53.599 --> 00:11:54.599
business.

00:11:54.799 --> 00:11:58.119
They actually do market research around sports technology.

00:11:58.119 --> 00:12:06.520
So things like in-venue betting and understanding how to engage fans in this new technical age,

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:11.280
biometric sensors on athletes, you name it, basically any sports technology.

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:15.039
And I like to call them kind of a market research company for sports tech.

00:12:15.039 --> 00:12:21.520
So what they have is a whole bunch of news articles that they collect via Feedly, DiffBot.

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:27.719
These are different third-party tools, and Leo is something that's, I believe, part of

00:12:27.719 --> 00:12:32.520
Feedly, and it analyzes all the information for you.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:37.599
It's kind of like a smart filter to bring in the information they care about.

00:12:37.599 --> 00:12:42.320
Okay, so the data is thousands of sports news articles.

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:45.359
There's also entity tagging that this Leo tool does.

00:12:45.359 --> 00:12:53.080
It tags sports teams, technologies, vendors, meaning vendors like Google, Microsoft, Nike,

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:58.440
technologies being anything from blockchain to augmented reality.

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:03.960
And so what we thought here was they wanted interesting news stories to be surfaced to them.

00:13:03.960 --> 00:13:07.919
So we simply took the number of mentions of these various entities over time.

00:13:07.919 --> 00:13:11.919
You could imagine Boston Red Sox are mentioned 10 times a week.

00:13:11.919 --> 00:13:13.280
Suddenly they're mentioned 30.

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:17.359
So we thought, okay, let's investigate why.

00:13:17.359 --> 00:13:19.640
So here's what the first iteration looks like.

00:13:19.640 --> 00:13:22.159
We have a date range.

00:13:22.159 --> 00:13:25.359
We have, they can filter by league if they'd like.

00:13:25.359 --> 00:13:32.159
We're looking at all leagues here, and we have a list of anomalies that our package bubbled up to the top.

00:13:32.159 --> 00:13:36.359
The Seattle Sounders here were detected.

00:13:36.359 --> 00:13:42.280
We click that, and it gives us a time series look at that particular anomaly.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:47.280
We can then click it and discover more about what's happening.

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:56.080
So on that date, and Shiny pops up this nice little module, the Seattle Sounders and Amazon work together.

00:13:56.080 --> 00:14:05.359
Amazon had acquired streaming rights for Prime Video soccer matches, and that's a huge thing that this company would like to know about.

00:14:05.359 --> 00:14:11.640
So from there, you could see how you can rapid prototype, and it might be manual, and you surface some anomalies.

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:14.479
But you could imagine how this could be automated into report.

00:14:14.479 --> 00:14:17.119
Give me the five most interesting stories that week.

00:14:17.119 --> 00:14:23.880
Give me the teams that are spiking in the news, and so on.

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:28.840
Another cool use case for them was we used it, it doubled as a QC tool.

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:32.159
So certain things would be spiking that shouldn't be.

00:14:32.159 --> 00:14:36.760
For example, the Ottawa Senators, they weren't doing particularly well.

00:14:36.760 --> 00:14:38.119
There was really no reason.

00:14:38.119 --> 00:14:40.280
It wasn't like the playoffs or anything.

00:14:40.280 --> 00:14:41.479
This is an NHL team.

00:14:41.479 --> 00:14:51.760
So we decided to dig into it, and it turned out that DiffBot was tagging OTT for the Ottawa Senators, because that's their abbreviation.

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:55.080
But it also stands for over-the-top streaming services.

00:14:55.080 --> 00:14:57.960
So we had identified a problem with the tagging.

00:14:57.960 --> 00:15:02.640
We alerted DiffBot, and we got that all fixed on the data itself.

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:09.599
So it can also be used as a data QC tool, not only to surface interesting things, but potentially problematic things,

00:15:09.599 --> 00:15:17.479
as we talked about also in the first example of finding hardware failures.

00:15:17.479 --> 00:15:22.520
And I'm leaving, I think, at least four minutes for questions, but final thoughts.

00:15:22.520 --> 00:15:24.000
Again, working with people is the hardest thing.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:33.080
We're lucky that usually people we've worked with so far understand the problem, and they're very collaborative.

00:15:33.080 --> 00:15:41.000
And I think being able to show them these results piecemeal is what built up the confidence and their understanding of the tool and why it matters.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:53.799
Giving them the why or allowing them to dig in to the why and explore more on their own is that sort of self-service and freedom of analysis that they need to really feel like they're engaged.

00:15:54.039 --> 00:16:01.599
So Shiny's been just incredible for that, because I remember the days where you just had to show them static charts and put together a PowerPoint,

00:16:01.599 --> 00:16:05.880
and it's very much like I'm just talking to you rather than working together.

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:11.239
So anomaly detection is a useful data-driven tool when used appropriately.

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:17.760
In our cases, we had identified specific needs for each scenario and tailored them accordingly.

00:16:18.520 --> 00:16:22.039
The first use case was for proactively identifying hardware failures.

00:16:22.520 --> 00:16:29.239
We learned over time that incorporating their threshold limits would actually give us more accurate results rather than just relying on the data.

00:16:30.359 --> 00:16:34.479
And the other use case surfaced interesting news stories as well as doubled as a data QC tool.

00:16:35.919 --> 00:16:42.039
Always work closely with your end users via that iterative process. Shiny, again, is fantastic for this.

00:16:42.760 --> 00:16:44.640
I always say build fast and fail quickly.

00:16:45.119 --> 00:16:48.719
I'd rather show you something that you think is terrible and you tear it apart.

00:16:48.719 --> 00:16:51.960
And getting that constructive criticism, to me, is a good sign.

00:16:51.960 --> 00:16:54.719
It means you're invested. It means you have ideas.

00:16:54.719 --> 00:16:58.080
And it means that we can improve upon it very fast.

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:01.960
And then don't leave out important business logic where it can help you.

00:17:02.200 --> 00:17:06.760
We don't always have to just rely on statistical models and assume it's going to solve all our problems.

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:11.520
There's oftentimes that we can incorporate that domain knowledge and it can really improve our results.

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:18.479
So always be looking for those pieces of logic that can help your automation or your math or your R package.

00:17:18.719 --> 00:17:24.319
